### Further details on related work

There has been a lot of work on computational computational hardness of sparse PCA [1, 2, 3].

**Minimax optimal Sparse PCA algorithms with global convergence:** These consist of SDP-based algorithms such as [13, 14, 2], which do not scale well in high-dimensions (see [3, 15]). The state-of-the-art SDP solvers [16, 17] currently have a runtime \(\Omega\left(n^{\omega}+d^{\omega}\right)\), where \(\omega\approx 2.732\) is the matrix multiplication exponent. Algorithms proposed in [18, 19, 10] involve forming the entire \((d\times d)\) sample covariance matrix, which can itself be challenging from the perspective of space and time complexity. Furthermore, [18, 19] have been analyzed under the _spiked covariance model_ in Eq 2. [11] propose a computationally efficient modification of the Fantope projection-based algorithm of [12], which requires \(O(d^{2})\) space, and \(\Omega(nd^{2})\) time.

**Single-pass online sparse PCA algorithms with \(O(d^{2})\) storage and \(O(nd^{2})\) time**[11] also provide a single-pass online algorithm and state that this algorithm (Theorem 4) _is the first to provably obtain the global optima in a streaming setting without any initialization, under a general \(\Sigma\)_. However, this method requires \(O(d^{2})\) storage, \(O(nd^{2})\) time, and the estimation error is \(O\left(\frac{d^{2}}{\sqrt{n}}\right)\) (Theorem 4, [11]). The algorithm does \(d\) sparse linear regression problems to achieve this.

**Support recovery algorithms with \(O(d^{2})\) storage and \(O(nd^{2})\) time** : [16, 17] use an SDP-based approach and [1] use sparse linear regression for support recovery.

**More details on streaming PCA algorithms**[12] provides an online block version of the truncated power method in [12] under the spiked model (Eq 2). They require an initialization \(u_{0}\) with a sufficiently large \(\left|u_{0}^{T}v_{1}\right|=\Omega\left(1\right)\) (local convergence). Their proposed initialization with streaming PCA algorithm until reaching a specific accuracy threshold, for which there is no known theoretical guarantee under the spiked high-dimensional setting. [18] provides an analysis of streaming sparse PCA under Eq 2 via partial differential equations (PDE), but they only prove asymptotic convergence. Similar to [12], they also require \(\left|u_{0}^{T}v_{1}\right|=\Omega\left(1\right)\) which can be hard to find in high dimensions for a general \(\Sigma\). Recent results provide a black-box way to obtain the top-\(k\) principal components (\(k\)-PCA) given an algorithm to extract the top eigenvector (see [1] which could be employed treating our algorithm as a 1-PCA oracle (see [16, 17]). We believe that our analysis can be extended to obtain top-k principal components simultaneously via QR decomposition and thresholding.

